<HEADLINE>
<P>
COLLEGE FOOTBALL REPORT WEEKDAY UPDATE; 
</P>
<P>
SAN DIEGO STATE; 
</P>
<P>
AZTECS TO GET NATIONAL ATTENTION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAVE McKIBBEN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
If the San Diego State football program ever wanted to make a positive 
impression on the nation, it will have the opportunity to do so Saturday. 
CBS-TV announced Monday that the SDSU-Brigham Young game, which begins at 12:13 
p.m., will be shown to 80% of the country. 
</P>
<P>
The other 20% will see a Southeast Conference game between Georgia and Alabama. 
</P>
<P>
The SDSU-BYU game had been scheduled to be regionally televised, but because of 
the interest in Heisman Trophy contender Ty Detmer and the Cougar team, which 
is ranked fourth by UPI. 
</P>
<P>
"We feel we have a great opportunity this week to show some people our 
program," Aztec Coach Al Luginbill said. "Just for us to be able and execute 
against a good football team will be interesting." 
</P>
<P>
The Aztecs will be without the services of freshman linebacker Jamal Duff 
Saturday. Duff missed Saturday's Long Beach State game with a deep contusion of 
his thigh. Trainer Brian Barry said he is being cautious with Duff's injury, 
saying if the bruise does not heal fully, the bone could form in the muscle. 
"We're not going to play Jamal until he's completely healthy," Luginbill said. 
. . . Running back Tommy Booker, who missed most of the second half Saturday 
with an ankle contusion, missed practice with the stomach flu. Barry said he is 
doubtful for Saturday because of the ankle. . . . Safety Zac Stokes, who 
fractured his shoulder early in the preseason, is healthy and ready to play. . 
. . Luginbill announced that freshman safety Sam Williford of Pasadena became 
the 23rd SDSU player to redshirt -- the same number that redshirted last 
season. DAVE McKIBBEN 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA091890-0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 278082 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
September 18, 1990, Tuesday, Valley Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Sports; Part C; Page 6; Column 4 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
118 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
VALLEY SPORTS ROUNDUP; 
</P>
<P>
CLAREMONT DEFEATS OCCIDENTAL IN SOCCER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Claremont's Marial Davis scored all of her team's goals Monday at Claremont to 
pace the home team to a 3-1 win over Occidental College in a Southern 
California Intercollegiate Athletic Conference women's soccer game. 
</P>
<P>
Jos Bergmann, a senior striker for Occidental, scored the Tigers' only goal in 
the first half. Occidental took 14 shots on goal to Claremont's eight. 
Occidental goalie Janet Hubbel notched three saves for the Tigers. 
</P>
<P>
The win evened Claremont's conference record to 1-1. Occidental fell to 1-1. 
</P>
<P>
In other women's games: 
</P>
<P>
Cal Lutheran 12, LaVerne 0 -- Vanessa Martin scored four goals and Rachel 
Wackerman added three to pace Cal Lutheran (2-1) to a non-conference win at 
LaVerne. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Game Story 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA091890-0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 278083 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
September 18, 1990, Tuesday, Valley Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Sports; Part C; Page 6; Column 4 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
103 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
VALLEY SPORTS ROUNDUP; 
</P>
<P>
GIRLS' VOLLEYBALL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Sylmar d. Verdugo Hills, 15-4, 15-9, 15-5 -- Andrea Cervantes had 13 aces and 
seven assists to pace host Sylmar in a non-league season opener for both teams. 
</P>
<P>
